2. The Problem We’re Solving
The tricky thing about symptoms is that they overlap a lot. A fever could mean the Flu, but it could also mean Malaria, Typhoid, or even just a bad Cold. If you tried to solve this with simple if-else logic, the code would get complicated really fast and still be inaccurate because you’re forcing binary answers onto something that is inherently probabilistic.

Think about it this way — our Unit 3 slides gave the example of a patient with a stiff neck. The probability of meningitis given a stiff neck turned out to be only 0.0002, even though stiff neck is strongly associated with meningitis. That’s because the prior probability of meningitis in the general population is so low. That example really stuck with me because it shows how just looking at one symptom is not enough. You need to weigh it against how common or rare the disease actually is.

By using Bayesian inference, I wanted to build something that doesn’t just give a yes or no answer, but instead ranks the possibilities. The goal was to take prior knowledge — how common a disease is in the population — and update it with evidence — the symptoms the user enters — to find the most likely diagnosis.

3. The Logic — Bayes’ Theorem
The entire engine of this program runs on one formula from Unit 3. We are trying to calculate P(D|S) — the probability of a disease D given that we observe a specific set of symptoms S.

P(D | S)  =  P(S | D)  ×  P(D)  ÷  P(S)

In my code I broke this down into three separate pieces:

•	The Prior P(D): How likely is this disease in the general population? For example a Cold is more common than COVID so it starts with a higher prior.
•	The Likelihood P(S|D): If someone definitely has the Flu, how likely are they to have a fever? This is stored in the symptoms_prob dictionary.
•	The Posterior P(D|S): This is the final answer — the updated probability after combining the prior with the evidence from the symptoms.

The normalisation step is what converts everything into proper percentages. Without it, you would just get raw scores like 0.0023 which don’t mean much. Dividing each score by the total of all scores makes them sum to 100%, which is the P(S) denominator in Bayes’ Rule.

I want to be honest here — normalisation was the part that confused me the most at first. I kept getting tiny decimal numbers and didn’t understand what they meant. It only clicked when I re-read the slide where it says P(S) is just a scaling constant to make sure all probabilities add up to 1.

